[1.7 Database and Application Architecture]
	- "shared-memory" server architectures
		-> multiple CPU's and exploit parallel processing
		-> all the CPU's access a common shared memory.

	- "parallel databases"
		-> desgined to run on a cluster consisting of multiple machines.

	- "distributed databases"
		-> allow data storage and query processing across multiple geographically separated machines.

	- "two-tier architecture"
		-> app resides at the client machine, and invokes database system functionality at the server machine through query language statements.

	- "three-tier architecture"
		-> modern database apps use
		-> client machine acts as a front end and does not contain any direct db calls.

		-> web browser and mobile apps are the most commonly used app clients

		-> frontend communicates with an app server.

		-> app server communicates with a database system to access data.

		* business logic of the app is embedded in the application server, instead of being distributed across multiple clients.

		-> better security as well as better performance than two-tier apps.